{"title_page": "Casar Jacobson", "text_new": "{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name         = Casar Jacobson\n| image        = Casar Jacobson 2008-07-20.JPG\n| caption      = Casar Jacobson (2008)\n| education    = \n| alma_mater   = <!-- Alma mater  -->\n| occupation   = \n| years_active = \n| birth_name   =Caesar C Jacobson \n| alias        = \n| birth_date   =\n| eye_color    = \n| eye_colour   = \n| hair_color   = \n| hair_colour  = \n| weight       = <!-- {{convert|0|kg|lb st|abbr=on|lk=on}} -->\n                 <!-- or {{convert|0|lb|st kg|abbr=on|lk=on}} -->\n                 <!-- or {{convert|0.0|st|kg lb|abbr=on|lk=on}} -->\n| title        = Miss Sun and Salsa 2010 <br /> Miss Calgary 2011 <br /> Miss Universe Canada 2012 <br /> Miss British Columbia 2012/2013 <br /> Miss Canada 2013  <br /> Miss Globe 2013 \n| competitions = Miss Calgary <br /> Miss Universe Canada <br /> Miss British Columbia <br /> Miss Canada <br /> Miss Canada Globe\n| films        = ''Talk to The Hands'', ''[[The Good Doctor (2011 film)|The Good Doctor]]'', ''[[The Murders]]''\n}}\n'''Casar Jacobson''' Is a Norwegian/Canadian Deaf activist. She is a disability, equality and gender rights activist, and United Nations Women Youth Champion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.unwomen.org/en/news/stories/2017/4/from-where-i-stand-casar-jacobson|title=From where I stand: \"Technology sees skills before gender and disability\"|work=UN Women|access-date=2017-06-20|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.un.org/sustainabledevelopment/blog/2017/03/international-womens-day-spotlights-impact-of-changing-world-of-work-2/|title=IW's Day spotlights impact of changing world of work|date=2017-03-07|work=United Nations Sustainable Development|access-date=2017-06-20|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4694983/united-nations-international-womens-day/|title=Watch Live as the United Nations Celebrates International Women's Day|last=Begley|first=Sarah|website=Time|access-date=2017-06-20}}</ref>  She has also been a successful pageant contestant, winning multiple titles, including Miss Canada Globe.<ref name=\"housefreepress\">{{cite news|last=Berrington|first=Reg|title=Katelynn Dow: pageant provides experience of a lifetime|newspaper=100 Mile House Free Press|publisher=Torstar|date=September 12, 2012|page=3|quote=The winner of the Miss Canada Globe Pageant was 26-year-old Vancouver resident Casar Jacobson.}}</ref><ref name=\"vancouverobserver1\">{{cite web|last=Marion|first=Kelly|title=Fancy hats and fashion with \"Ladies Who Lunch\"|url=http://www.vancouverobserver.com/blogs/beevancity/fancy-hats-and-fashion-ladies-who-lunch?page=0,1|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407085320/http://www.vancouverobserver.com/blogs/beevancity/fancy-hats-and-fashion-ladies-who-lunch?page=0%2C1|archivedate=April 7, 2014|work=vancouverobserver.com|accessdate=April 4, 2014|page=2|date=October 13, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> She aspires to one day become a doctor and is focusing on her studies while working in Health Care and in the communities of British Columbia and Toronto, Ontario.\n\n\n== Early life ==\nJacobson is of [[Norwegian people|Norwegian]]-Canadian descent. She was born in [[Austria]] and lived in [[Norway]] and [[Germany]], where she graduated from university with a master's degree in [[genetics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.startasl.com/famous-deaf-people_html|title=Famous Deaf People \u2013 Start ASL|website=www.startasl.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-06-20}}</ref> She moved to Canada at 21. She wanted to work with people and became the first Deaf person to graduate as an HCA in Canada; a nine-month Health Care Assistant program rolled out in 2017 in the province of British Columbia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vancouverisawesome.com/sponsored/health-care-assistants-vancouver-1946586|title=Health Care Assistants Vancouver|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\nJacobson is bilaterally and profoundly deaf, utilizing [[American Sign Language]].{{Citation needed|date=2 April 2020}} As a child she was involved in arts such as jazz dancing, belly dancing and salsa.{{Citation needed|date=2 April 2020}}\n\n== Acting Career ==\nIn 2012 Jacobson was a production assistant and driver with Canada's Got Talent, which featured [[Martin Short]], [[Dina Pugliese]] and [[Measha Brueggergosman]]. She organized the competition categories and the long line-ups of contestants. [[Canada's Got Talent]] was on [[Citytv|CityTV]] but was subsequently cancelled and ran for only one season.{{Citation needed|date=2 April 2020}}\n\nJacobson appeared in [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC's]] [[The Good Doctor (TV series)|The Good Doctor]] alongside English actor [[Freddie Highmore]].{{Citation needed|date=2 April 2020}} An international, two-part, medical documentary featuring Casar Jacobson is set for release in December 2020.{{Citation needed|date=2 April 2020}}\n\n== Pageant Career ==\nIn 2012 she was selected as \"audience favourite\" in [[Miss Universe Canada]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.criticalbeauty.com/2012/05/miss-universe-canada-2012-crowned.html|title=Miss Universe Canada 2012 crowned|website=www.criticalbeauty.com|access-date=2017-06-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524221418/http://www.criticalbeauty.com/2012/05/miss-universe-canada-2012-crowned.html|archivedate=2012-05-24}}</ref><ref name=torontosun1>{{cite news|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2012/05/18/miss-universe-canada-kicks-off|accessdate=February 27, 2014|title=Miss Universe Canada kicks off|newspaper=Toronto Sun|date=May 18, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Transgender beauty contestant takes spotlight from rivals|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/transgender-beauty-contestant-takes-spotlight-from-rivals-1.1242246|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305075713/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/transgender-beauty-contestant-takes-spotlight-from-rivals-1.1242246|archivedate=March 5, 2014|work=CBC News|publisher=CBC/Canadian Press|accessdate=February 28, 2014|date=May 17, 2012|quote=Vancouver's Casar Jacobson got the night's most audience votes}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/artslife/97783-reaction-mixed-to-transgender-contestant-at-miss-universe-canada|title=Reaction mixed to transgender contestant at Miss Universe Canada|date=2014-04-14|work=The Chronicle Herald|access-date=2017-06-20|language=en}}</ref> In 2013 she won the title Miss British Columbia Globe 2012/2013.<ref name=\"misscanada\">{{cite web|title=Miss Canada Globe|url=http://www.misscanada.tv/pb/wp_95ed75a4/wp_95ed75a4.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304000013/http://www.misscanada.tv/pb/wp_95ed75a4/wp_95ed75a4.html|archivedate=March 4, 2014|work=MissCanada.tv|accessdate=February 27, 2014}}</ref> After that, she became Miss Canada Globe 2013.<ref name=\"businessedge\">{{cite news|title = Canadian Beauty Queen Competes for Miss Globe|url = http://www.businessedge.ca/pdf/BusinessEdge-2012-11.pdf|accessdate = February 27, 2014|newspaper = Business Edge|date = November 2012}}</ref> She traveled to [[Albania]] to compete in the Miss Globe pageant, in which she was awarded the title of \"Miss Peace\".<ref name=\"missglobe2012\">{{cite web|title=Miss Globe 2012|url=http://www.themissglobe.com/2012/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305042544/http://www.themissglobe.com/2012/|archivedate=March 5, 2014|work=TheMissGlobe.com|accessdate=February 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!| Year\n!| Title\n!| Result\n|-\n|2008\n|[[Sun and Salsa Festival|Miss Sun and Salsa]]\n|n/a\n|-\n|2010\n|Miss Sun and Salsa\n|Winner\n|-\n|2011\n|Miss Calgary\n|Winner\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Miss Universe Canada 2012|Miss Universe Canada]]\n|Audience Favourite <br /> (consolation)\n|-\n|2012/2013\n|Miss British Columbia Globe\n|Winner\n|-\n|2013\n|Miss Canada Globe\n|Winner\n|-\n|2013\n|Miss Globe\n|Miss Peace <br /> (consolation)\n|}\n[[File:C\u00e4sar seen here with Estonian sisters; Leila, Liina and Lily.jpg|Jacobson (2nd from left) in Greece at Paralympics related event in 2017|thumb]]\n\n== Disability rights activist ==\nHaving lost her hearing in both ears, Jacobson is profoundly deaf. She is a disability activist and [[gender equality]] spokesperson for [[United Nations Global Compact|UN Global Compact]] Canada.<ref>http://globalcompact.ca/genderequality2017/casar-jacobson/\n</ref> Working with the [[United Nations]] entity as a Youth Champion and Planet 50/50 champion on Women Empowerment, Gender Equality, and a sub-sector in disabilities, Deaf culture and entrepreneurialism she also is involved in women's organizations and projects for women with disabilities worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://unsdn.org/2017/06/13/amplifying-the-voices-of-women-with-disabilities/|title=Amplifying the voices of women with disabilities|last=UNSDN|date=2017-06-13|website=UNSDN - United Nations Social Development Network|access-date=2017-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unmultimedia.org/radio/english/2017/03/we-need-more-innovation-disability-advocate/#.WUhsLDOB3BI|title=\"We need more innovation\": disability advocate {{!}} United Nations Radio|date=2017-03-09|website=www.unmultimedia.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-06-20}}</ref> Jacobson became the first Deaf person from Canada and Norway at The UN Observance of International Women's Day 2017, participating in a panel discussion with [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Bjarni Benediktsson (born 1970)|Bjarni Benediktsson]], Ravi Karkara, [[Phumzile Mlambo-Ngcuka|Phumzile Mlambo]] and [[Lakshmi Puri]] of the United Nations, as well as [[Ant\u00f3nio Guterres]] and [[Amina J. Mohammed|Amina Mohammed]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://womenwatch.unwomen.org/international-womens-day|title=International Women's Day {{!}} UN Women Watch|website=womenwatch.unwomen.org|language=en|access-date=2017-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/youthenvoy/2017/03/in-nairobi-un-chief-guterres-marks-international-womens-day-by-meeting-with-young-women-in-mathare-slum/|title=In Nairobi, UN chief Guterres marks International Women's Day by meeting with young women in Mathare slum.|website=www.un.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.unwomen.org/en/news/stories/2017/2/media-advisory-international-womens-day-8-march-2017|title=Media Advisory: International Women's Day, 8 March|work=UN Women|access-date=2017-06-20|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1448000/women-day-spotlights-impact-changing-world|title=Women's Day spotlights impact of changing world of work|work=www.newvision.co.ug|access-date=2017-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ca.news.yahoo.com/watch-live-united-nations-celebrates-150257528.html|title=Watch Live as the United Nations Celebrates International Women's Day|access-date=2017-06-20|language=en-CA}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://casarjacobson.com Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jacobson, Casar}}\n[[Category:Canadian beauty pageant winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Deaf people from Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian disability rights activists]]\n[[Category:Youth activists]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from Canada]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name         = Casar Jacobson\n| image        = Casar Jacobson 2008-07-20.JPG\n| caption      = Casar Jacobson (2008)\n| education    = \n| alma_mater   = <!-- Alma mater  -->\n| occupation   = \n| years_active = \n| birth_name   =Caesar C Jacobson \n| alias        = \n| birth_date   =\n| eye_color    = \n| eye_colour   = \n| hair_color   = \n| hair_colour  = \n| weight       = <!-- {{convert|0|kg|lb st|abbr=on|lk=on}} -->\n                 <!-- or {{convert|0|lb|st kg|abbr=on|lk=on}} -->